title: Protests in Egypt
name: Protests in Egypt
description: Supporters of President Hosni Mubarak attacked anti-government protesters Wednesday in Tahrir Square. Molotov cocktails ignited small fires and military forces used water canon to dampen the violence. The Egyptian health minister reported three people killed.

properties.name: Mohandessin
properties.description: 20,000 people walked from Mohandessin toward the center of Cairo.

properties.name: 6 October Bridge
properties.description: Al Jazeera television footage showed protests on the 6 October Bridge.

properties.name: Kasr Al_Nile Bridge
properties.description: Riot police fired water cannons at protesters attempting to cross the Kasr Al Nile Bridge.

properties.name: Tahrir Square
properties.description: Protesters loyal to President Hosni Mubarak fought with anti-government demonstrators Wednesday in Tahrir Square and the surrounding streets.

properties.name: Al-Azhar Mosque
properties.description: Police fired rubber bullets at thousands of protesters gathered outside the Al-Azhar Mosque.

properties.name: Suez
properties.description: Two protesters killed in clashes with police during demonstrations Tuesday.

properties.name: Alexandria
properties.description: Saturday: Police fire live ammunition and teargas against protesters; demonstrations continue after curfew.Wednesday: About 200 protesters attempt to gather in central squares. Dozens detained.

properties.name: Ismalia
properties.description: Thursday: Hundreds of protesters dispersed by police with teargas.

properties.name: Kafr El-Sheikh
properties.description: Wednesday: Police blockaded a village.

properties.name: El Mahalla el Kubra
properties.description: Wednesday: Police dispersed would-be protesters.

properties.name: Sheikh Zoweid
properties.description: One Bedouin protester killed after being shot in the head by security forces.

properties.name: Nasser Metro Station
properties.description: Wednesday: Police beat protesters with batons.

properties.name: Egypt Museum
properties.description: Protestors smash statutes and damage mummies

properties.name: National Democratic Party HQ
properties.description: Saturday: Building continues to burn; no firefighters responding

properties.name: National television and radio station HQ
properties.description: Friday: Demonstrators attempted to enter the state TV headquarters. There was no major army presence in the area.

properties.name: Cairo Airport
properties.description: As many as 3,000 people reported stranded as several airlines cancel or suspend flights. Other Arab nations including Saudi Arabia, Jordan and Lebanon organize flights to take their citizens out of Egypt.

properties.name: Gaza Strip
properties.description: Residents crowd gas stations as protests in Egypt impede fuel smuggling through tunnels running from Egypt.

properties.name: Corniche promenade
properties.description: Residents defy curfew; chat with soldiers who take no action to disperse them.

properties.name: Ministry of Interior
properties.description: Saturday: Police use tear gas on protesters moving toward ministry building.

properties.name: Fayoum
properties.description: Saturday: About 700 prisoners escaped jail, reportedly killing a police officer.

properties.name: Beni Suef
properties.description: Saturday: Police kill 17 people trying to attack two police stations.

properties.name: Rabat, Morocco
properties.description: July 1: Morocco voted on a new constitution that will likely result in passage. Supporters, including the king, say the new document would result in more political freedoms. Opponents counter, saying it will leave the monarchy still in charge with no real change.

properties.name: Kismayo, Somalia
properties.description: July 1: American troops landed here to pick up the bodies of dead and wounded militants after a drone strike. The Somali government has urged the U.S. to strike more often at the al-Qaeda-linked members of al-Shabab. The fear is the Somali group will develop ties with the Yemen-based al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula.

properties.name: Homs, Syria
properties.description: July 1: Government forces shot and killed at least three demonstrators. Witnesses say armored cars were deployed and that soldiers shot at protesters from roadblocks. Syria has been seen continuous protests for two and a half months, seeking an end to the regime of President Bashar Assad.

properties.name: Misurata, Libya
properties.description: July 1: A spokesman for Libya's rebels here says negotiations are in progress with the French government to supply ammunition and weapons. The French did not confirm the statement but they have supplied rebels in other parts of the country with arms.

properties.name: Approximate boundary of coalition no-fly zone
Cairo, Egypt
properties.description: July 8: With the nation facing rising anxieties over a new constitution, parliamentary elections and next month's trial of former President Hosni Mubarak, protesters again filled Tahrir Square, ground zero for political demonstrations. Mubarak was depicted with a noose around his neck in posters across the square.

properties.name: Sanaa, Yemen
properties.description: July 8: President Ali Abdullah Saleh's supporters staged rallies at his vacant palace following his appearance Thursday on state-run televsion. Saleh is in Saudi Arabia recovering from a bomb blast at his palace. He did not offer a date on which he plans to return to power, setting off speculation as to whether he will, or, for that matter, whether his Saudi hosts will allow him to do so.

properties.name: Amman, Jordan
properties.description: July 8: About 300 protesters outside the office of Prime Minister Marouf Bakhit heard Jordan's Islamist leader criticize the nation's intelligence force. The Islamic Action Front's Hamza Mansour claimed security forces control the government and limit free expression.

properties.name: Damascus, Syria
properties.description: July 8: Security forces killed at least three people while breaking up a demonstration against President Bashar Assad's regime, according the activists. The forces reportedly used smoke and gunfire to quell the overnight protest.

properties.name: Diraz, Bahrain
properties.description: July 8: Sheik Isa Qassim, Bahrain's most important Shiite Muslim cleric, delivered a sermon criticizing reconciliation talks between the kingdom's Sunni rulers and Shiite opposition groups. Five months of protests by Shiites demanding political reforms and more freedom have led to the deaths of at least 32 people as well as the imprisonment of many others.

properties.name: Tripoli, Libya
properties.description: July 8: Thousands of President Moammar Kadafi's backers gathered in the city's Green Square for prayers and and a pro-government show of support. A Libyan cleric told those gathered the rebellion would end soon and that the country was competent to instigate reform without interference from Western nations.

properties.name: Hama, Syria
properties.description: July 8: Tens of thousands of people demanding the downfall of Syria's autocratic regime poured into the streets in a powerful rebuttal to both President Bashar Assad's much-doubted entreaties to dialogue and his use of force to suppress a revolt against his rule. Video footage  showed crowds as far as the eye could see in the city infamous for a brutal 1982 crackdown by Assad's father and predecessor, Hafez Assad, against an Islamist revolt.

properties.name: Maaret al-Numan, Syria
properties.description: July 8: Three protesters were killed by security forces, according to a human rights activist. Five others were killed in other cities, including Damascus and Homs. Syria's ban on foreign reporters makes independent confirmation of deaths very difficult.

properties.name: Tel Aviv, Israel
properties.description: July 8: Israeli authorities refused entry into the country for a pair of pro-Palestinian activists from the U.S. They were planning to take part in a Welcome to Palestine week of events in the West Bank. Activists from the U.S. and Europe are booked on flights to arrive in Israel on Friday and will be closely questioned by security personnel.

properties.name: Sohar, Oman
properties.description: July 8: A small demonstration called for the release of protesters who were jailed earlier this year. The city has been at the center of protests here, which have been relatively peaceful compared to others in the Arab world. They also have differed in tone, calling mostly for more jobs, higher wages and an end to corruption as opposed to political reform.
